<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Mike Rawson (HSR 003)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:20pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from Mike Rawson (HSR 003)</span></p><p style="font-size:20pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">             </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:18pt">SUMMARY</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:18pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The North – South Railway</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">HS2 is fundamentally flawed</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The alternative to HS2</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Options </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">in the capitol</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Cheaper construction costs</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">High Speed comparisons</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Capacity comparisons</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">8   The 3 hour journey </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">target</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> – London - Scotland</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">HS2, Britain’s second High Speed Rail project, will not deliver benefits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">which will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">reflect the enormous costs involv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ed in its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">construction. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The objectives are clear, the solution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> offered by HS2,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> is wrong. A new North – South Railway </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">must double </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">capacity on the East &amp; West Coast routes whilst offering </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">direct </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">services to the continent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">from The Midlands and The North of E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ngland to encourage the switch from the plane to the train to reduce carbon emissions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The new railway must take the rare opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">construct</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">through London’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">services to connect the north and the south of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">the country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">In the heart of the capitol i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">t must </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> excellent connectivity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">with CROSSRAIL </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">services to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Heathrow Airport, The City and Canary Wharf </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">as well as to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> London Underground services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Why is HS2 fundamentally flawed? The Y Route, London to Manchester and Leeds via Birmingham </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">only doubles </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">capacity on the two classic routes from the capitol to the north once the line </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">diverges </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">NORTH of Birmingham.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The design of the route means ALL trains from London will call at Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> making the route between the capitol and Leeds illogical</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> and the journey </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">between</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> Leeds </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> the continent, absurd.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">It is planned for HS2 trains to depart from Leeds, travel south west to Birmingham, continue past Aylesbury in Buckinghamshire, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">travel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">through Hillingdon, Ruislip and Acton in West London, enter a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Victorian tunnel around North London to Stratford in East London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> before joining HS1 tracks to Folkestone and the Channel Tunnel!</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Little wonder the airlines are unconcerned by HS2 – the train offers no serious threat to the seventy minute flight from Leeds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">/ Bradford to Paris.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">It should be remembered a part of the justification of the cost of HS2 is the reduction in carbon emissions. As the route of HS2 will ensure no reduction in flights to the near continent the claim is spurious.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The Prime Minister insis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ts there is absolutely no alternative to HS2. With all due respect to Mr Cameron, he is wrong!</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The suggested alternative to HS2 is a new build North – South railway known as EAST &amp; WEST COAST 2. This railway is designed to ensure capacity on the two </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">routes from the capitol to the north is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">doubled.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Starting in the very heart of the capitol (possibly at the new £1bn Tottenham Court Road CROSSRAIL Station) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">four tracks, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">in tunnels for eight miles beneath North London, follow the traditional transport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">corr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">idor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> of the M1 Motorway.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Near Junction 19</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> the tracks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">diverge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">with one route following the M6 to Birmingham and Manchester whilst the other route follows the M1 to East Midlands Parkway and Leeds.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">triangle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">design, where the tracks diverge, enables </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">superb connectivity between towns and cities in The Midlands and The North of England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The new railway offers several interesting options in the capitol. Unlike HS2, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">planned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> to terminate at Euston, the alternative scheme allows for the provision of both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">terminus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">platforms in the centre of London (trains from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">orth </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">of England </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">continue to Clapham Junction and the south coast).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">As the railway is below ground in London it allows for a spur to Kings Cross/St Pancras as well as a short link, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">fro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">m </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">north of Kings Cross station, to HS1 tracks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">providing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">attractive </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">‘through’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">services from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The North to the Continent.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">A connection with LONDON OVERGROUND services at Finchley Road contributes to a reduction in potential overcrowding in the central London </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">statio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">n whilst </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> passengers with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">numerous</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> onward journey </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">options.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">EAST &amp; WEST COAST 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> follows an entirely different route to that proposed by HS2 Ltd. It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> uses 140mph </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">tilting trains, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">making construction of the track cheaper as it follows natural </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">changes in the landscape avoiding designated areas to reduce disruption whilst keeping losses to an absolute minimum.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The trains are generally restricted to 140mph, except where straight sections of track permit a higher speed, but are capable of speeds of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> 200mph when operating on the continent. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">A comparison of journey times at different speeds makes interesting reading!</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">225mph (the projected speed of HS2) is a little less than four miles per minute. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">140mph (on average the speed of EAST &amp; WEST COAST 2 t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">rains) is a little less than two and half miles per minute.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The time difference for a 100 mile journey is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">ten minutes!</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Unlike France, Spain and China</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> our towns and cities are relatively close together</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> and 225mph trains are neither necessary nor justifie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">d.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 87.63pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">EAST &amp; WEST COAST 2 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">a High Speed Railway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> delivering </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">TWICE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">the capacity of HS2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> and will meet demand until the next millennium. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">It is effectively </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">TWO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Railways, with the section between London and Junction 19</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> in Leicestershire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">, running parallel.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The design permits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">twenty four trains per hour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">(twelve between London &amp; Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> via Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> and twelve between London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> &amp; Leeds via East Midlands Parkway)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">when running five minutes apart.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">HS2, by comparison, permits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">twelve trains per hour </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">(six </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">London </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&amp; Manchester via</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt"> and six between London &amp; Leeds via </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">Put another way, assuming a loading of 800 per train, HS2 will carry 9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">600 passengers per hour at peak operation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">East &amp; West Coast 2 will carry almost 20</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">000!</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">If, as govern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">ment claims, capacity is the major issue when it comes to investing in the future of our railways, HS2 comes a poor second!</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">The future goal is a three hour journey between London and Scotland’s two major cities. When the West Coast Main Line is upgraded to four tracks between Lancashire and Glasgow and the East Coast Main Line is upgraded to four tracks between Yorkshire and Ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">inburgh, EAST &amp; WEST COAST 2 will play a major part in achieving the goal.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>